holder, create a heightened state of awareness, convey a message, or produce a magical outcome, a transition, a transformation? After an introduction by the volume editors, Bell Yung proposes a theoretical framework for dealing with Chinese ritual sound. A group of three essays focuses on the music for rituals that create political and social legitimacy followed by a second group of essays considering the music associated with rites of passage. Two essays then deal with the music accompanying rituals of propitiation. In all these cases, music is seen to play a critical role, if not the core of the ritual.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 4aAnthropology -- Asia. 4aArt. 7aRELIGION / Christian Rituals & Practice / General.2bisacsh1 aBoltz, Judith Magee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJudd, Ellen R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLam, Joseph S. C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLi, Ping-Hui, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aProvine, Robert C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRawski, Evelyn S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRawski, Evelyn S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRees, Helen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWatson, Rubie S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWatson, Rubie S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aYung, Bell, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYung, Bell, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080476490240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804764902423Coveruhttps://ww